article.description:
Steve Francis had 26 points and Cuttino Mobley
added 19 as the Houston Rockets grabbed an early lead and beat the
Milwaukee Bucks 103-80 Tuesday night.
article.headline: Francis, Rockets hold Bucks to 80 points
article.linkText: Rockets get defensive in shutting down Bucks
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Houston's intensity proved to be too much for the Milwaukee Bucks.
Francis

The Rockets opened a big lead early in the game and coasted to a 103-80 victory over the Bucks Tuesday night. "I'm very disappointed with our effort,'' Milwaukee coach George Karl said. "We conceded the game early and didn't want to win it very badly. We just never met the level of intensity that Houston brought to the game.'' Sam Cassell led the Bucks with 22 points but didn't like the start time of 9 p.m. "It was terrible,'' Cassell said. "It would have been OK playing on New Year's Eve at 7 or 7:30 p.m. but 9 p.m. is too late.'' The Rockets got 26 points from Steve Francis, 19 from Cuttino Mobley and 16 from Yao Ming. "Obviously, this is a wonderful way to end one year and start another,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. "We had balance. A lot of guys got involved. The bench came in and did a great job.'' The teams were tied at 18 after the first quarter, but with Francis scoring 14 and the bench adding a total of 13, the Rockets pulled away to lead 50-36 at the half. "We were moving the ball well and everybody got good looks,'' Francis said. "It was good for us to get so many reserves in. Today I got to rest for a whole quarter, which is rare.'' Yao had 8 rebounds as Houston improved to 9-3 against Eastern Conference teams. Back-to-back 3s by Glen Rice and Mobley finished a 10-0 run that gave the Rockets a 68-46 lead with 5:39 left in the third. Yao had 10 and Francis nine in the period which ended with Houston leading 83-58. With Mobley scoring six and Yao adding four points and getting three rebounds, the Rockets jumped to an 18-8 lead seven minutes into the game. Cassell then led the Bucks on a 10-0 run, scoring six of his 10 first-quarter points, to tie at 18 with 1:21 left in the first. Late in the second quarter, Francis scored nine points in an 11-0 run that gave the Rockets a 43-32 lead with 1:41 to play. Francis had 14 in the quarter, including a 3 with less than a second left, as Houston led 50-36 at halftime. The Rockets led by as much as 28 points as reserves played most of the fourth. Game notes
The Bucks played without leading scorer Ray Allen, who sat out with a sore right ankle. ... The Rockets have held six teams to fewer than 80 points, matching the franchise record set in three other seasons, the last the 2000-2001. They are 5-1 in those games. ... Maurice Taylor left the game in the third quarter with a tightened Achilles tendon and did not return. ... Milwaukee, which beat Dallas Monday to go 3-5 in the first of back-to-back games, is 3-5 in the second games.
